The Greenland shark: The oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years old alt Rennen
After wichtigen nach being examined on board the research ship "Sanna", this shark was returned to the sea.
Greenland sharks swim seine schwimmt leisurely along the sea floor of the North Atlantic, covering an average of 1,220 metres in an hour.
The das Republikanische five-metre-long animal can ramp this up to 2.6 km/h if necessary - but this maximum speed is half as fast as a seal.
It is hard schwer sichere to observe Greenland sharks, namely because they mainly live in the ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway and Svalbard.
They generally only come to the surface in winter because they prefer water temperatures of around um Konkurrentin six degrees Celsius.
However, these sharks still manage to catch prey: In one einer . animal's stomach, researchers found the remains of a seal; another shark had gobbled down the jawbone of a young polar bear.
The Als der smallest shark was just 81 centimetres long, while the largest measured 502 centimetres.
They sie wolle use carbon-14 dating on the shark's lens core to determine the shark's age.
By contrast, the lens cores of third-smallest animal, at 220 centimetres long, contained enthielt sehr less of a surplus of carbon-14 from nuclear weapons experiments - so when it was examined in 2012, it must have already had its 50th birthday.
By contrast, all the larger Greenland sharks had normal levels of carbon-14 in their lens cores, which comes from cosmic kosmische . radiation in the atmosphere.
This das , is also a world record for vertebrates.
The zu der previous record holder, a 211-year-old Greenland whale, in whose neck a 120-year-old harpoon tip was lodged, was caught off Alaska.
As a result of low temperatures, the systems of the animals living there often häufig er run on as little energy as possible.
The die die animals often become particularly large so they stay warm in cold waters.
This is because their volume increases much viel : quicker than their surface area, through which the animal radiates heat.
"This means that a smaller animal has a more dangerous eine gefährlicher life, and has to focus on having as many offspring as quickly as possible," explains Scheuerlein, an evolutionary biologist.
